widl-Touch-pageX.name: pageX
widl-Touch-pageX.summary: The pageX read-only property of the MouseEvent interface returns the X (horizontal) coordinate (in pixels) at which the mouse was clicked, relative to the left edge of the entire document.
widl-Touch-pageX.title: MouseEvent.pageX

widl-Touch-pageX.name: pageX
widl-Touch-pageX.summary: The Touch.pageX read-only property returns the X coordinate of the touch point relative to the viewport, including any scroll offset.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-pageX.title: Touch.pageX

widl-Touch-pageY.name: pageY
widl-Touch-pageY.summary: The pageY read-only property of the MouseEvent interface returns the Y (vertical) coordinate in pixels of the event relative to the whole document. This property takes into account any vertical scrolling of the page.
widl-Touch-pageY.title: MouseEvent.pageY

widl-Touch-pageY.name: pageY
widl-Touch-pageY.summary: The Touch.pageY read-only property returns the Y coordinate of the touch point relative to the viewport, including any scroll offset.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-pageY.title: Touch.pageY

widl-Touch-clientX.name: clientX
widl-Touch-clientX.summary: The Touch.clientX read-only property returns the X coordinate of the touch point relative to the viewport, not including any scroll offset.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-clientX.title: Touch.clientX

widl-Touch-clientY.name: clientY
widl-Touch-clientY.summary: The Touch.clientY read-only property returns the Y coordinate of the touch point relative to the browser's viewport, not including any scroll offset.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-clientY.title: Touch.clientY

widl-Touch-identifier.name: identifier
widl-Touch-identifier.summary: The Touch.identifier returns a value uniquely identifying this point of contact with the touch surface. This value remains consistent for every event involving this finger's (or stylus's) movement on the surface until it is lifted off the surface.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-identifier.title: Touch.identifier

widl-Touch-screenX.name: screenX
widl-Touch-screenX.summary: Returns the X coordinate of the touch point relative to the screen, not including any scroll offset.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-screenX.title: Touch.screenX

widl-Touch-screenY.name: screenY
widl-Touch-screenY.summary: Returns the Y coordinate of the touch point relative to the screen, not including any scroll offset.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-screenY.title: Touch.screenY

widl-Touch-target.name: target
widl-Touch-target.summary: Returns the Element (EventTarget) on which the touch contact started when it was first placed on the surface, even if the touch point has since moved outside the interactive area of that element or even been removed from the document. Note that if the target element is removed from the document, events will still be targeted at it, and hence won't necessarily bubble up to the window or document anymore. If there is any risk of an element being removed while it is being touched, the best practice is to attach the touch listeners directly to the target.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

widl-Touch-target.title: Touch.target

touch-interface.name: Touch
touch-interface.summary: The Touch interface represents a single contact point on a touch-sensitive device. The contact point is commonly a finger or stylus and the device may be a touchscreen or trackpad.

firefox.notes: Touch events support has been fixed and reenabled in Windows desktop platforms.
Web compatibility issues seen in bug 888304.

touch-interface.title: Touch

widl-TouchEvent-altKey.name: altKey
widl-TouchEvent-altKey.summary: A Boolean value indicating whether or not the alt (Alternate) key is enabled when the touch event is created. If the alt key is enabled, the attribute's value is true. Otherwise, it is false.
widl-TouchEvent-altKey.title: TouchEvent.altKey

widl-TouchEvent-changedTouches.name: changedTouches
widl-TouchEvent-changedTouches.summary: The changedTouches read-only property is a TouchList whose touch points (Touch objects) varies depending on the event type, as follows:
widl-TouchEvent-changedTouches.title: TouchEvent.changedTouches

widl-TouchEvent-ctrlKey.name: ctrlKey
widl-TouchEvent-ctrlKey.summary: A Boolean value indicating whether the control (Control) key is enabled when the touch event is created. If this key is enabled, the attribute's value is true. Otherwise, it is false.
widl-TouchEvent-ctrlKey.title: TouchEvent.ctrlKey

widl-TouchEvent-metaKey.name: metaKey
widl-TouchEvent-metaKey.summary: A Boolean value indicating whether or not the Meta key is enabled when the touch event is created. If this key is enabled, the attribute's value is true. Otherwise, it is false.
widl-TouchEvent-metaKey.title: TouchEvent.metaKey

widl-TouchEvent-shiftKey.name: shiftKey
widl-TouchEvent-shiftKey.summary: A Boolean value indicating whether or not the shift key is enabled when the touch event is created. If this key is enabled, the attribute's value is true. Otherwise, it is false.
widl-TouchEvent-shiftKey.title: TouchEvent.shiftKey

widl-TouchEvent-targetTouches.name: targetTouches
widl-TouchEvent-targetTouches.summary: The targetTouches read-only property is a TouchList listing all the Touch objects for touch points that are still in contact with the touch surface and whose touchstart event occurred inside the same target element as the current target element.
widl-TouchEvent-targetTouches.title: TouchEvent.targetTouches

widl-TouchEvent-touches.name: touches
widl-TouchEvent-touches.summary: touches is a read-only TouchList listing all the Touch objects for touch points that are currently in contact with the touch surface, regardless of whether or not they've changed or what their target element was at touchstart time.
widl-TouchEvent-touches.title: TouchEvent.touches

touchevent-interface.name: TouchEvent
touchevent-interface.summary: The TouchEvent interface represents an UIEvent which is sent when the state of contacts with a touch-sensitive surface changes. This surface can be a touch screen or trackpad, for example. The event can describe one or more points of contact with the screen and includes support for detecting movement, addition and removal of contact points, and so forth.

firefox.notes: Removed in bug 888304 due to web compatibility issues.

touchevent-interface.title: TouchEvent

widl-TouchList-item-getter-Touch-unsigne.name: item
widl-TouchList-item-getter-Touch-unsigne.summary: The item() method returns the Touch object at the specified index in the TouchList.
widl-TouchList-item-getter-Touch-unsigne.title: TouchList.item()

widl-TouchList-length.name: length
widl-TouchList-length.summary: The length read-only property indicates the number of items (touch points) in a given TouchList.
widl-TouchList-length.title: TouchList.length

touchlist-interface.name: TouchList
touchlist-interface.summary: The TouchList interface represents a list of contact points on a touch surface. For example, if the user has three fingers on the touch surface (such as a screen or trackpad), the corresponding TouchList object would have one Touch object for each finger, for a total of three entries.
touchlist-interface.title: TouchList
